{{notability|date=November 2014}} {{Infobox journal | title = Philosophy Pathways | cover = | editor = Geoffrey Klempner | discipline = [[Philosophy]] | abbreviation = <!-- Philos. Pathw. --> | publisher = International Society for Philosophers | country = | frequency = Irregular | history = January 2001–present | openaccess = Yes | impact = | impact-year = | website = http://www.philosophypathways.com/newsletter/index.html | link1 = | link1-name = | link2 = | link2-name = | JSTOR = | OCLC = 50011425 | LCCN = | CODEN = | ISSN = 2043-0728 | eISSN = }} '''''Philosophy Pathways''''' is an [[open access]], [[transparent peer review]]ed, [[electronic journal]] in [[philosophy]].<ref>[http://arch.oucs.ox.ac.uk/detail/92315/index.html ISFP: profile] at the Arts and Humanities Community Resource, [[University of Oxford]]. Retrieved 12 October 2017.</ref> The [[editor-in-chief]] is Geoffrey Klempner, the former director of studies (1996&ndash;2002), [[Philosophical Society of England]]. It was established in January 2001 and is published by the partner organizations International Society for Philosophers (ISFP)<ref>[https://philosophypathways.com/newsletter/index.html Official website]. Retrieved 12 October 2017.</ref><ref>[https://philosophypathways.com/vita.html Geoffrey Klempner: Brief CV]. Retrieved 12 October 2017.</ref> and Pathways School of Philosophy (Pathways to Philosophy).<ref>[http://arch.oucs.ox.ac.uk/detail/92315/index.html Pathways to Philosophy: profile] at the Arts and Humanities Community Resource, [[University of Oxford]]. Retrieved 15 October 2017.</ref><ref>[https://philosophypathways.com/index.html Pathways to Philosophy: Official website]. Retrieved 15 October 2017.</ref>
== Reception == In January 2005, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' wrote, "The International Society for Philosophers, which is aimed at anyone interested in philosophy, now has 800 members in 68 countries, though it is only two years old. The society's magazine, Philosophy Pathways, goes out fortnightly to more than 1,000 addresses, and around 400 students from 40 countries have participated in its distance learning programme."<ref>Talbot, Marianne (21 January 2005). ''[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/3349129/I-link-therefore-I-am.html I link, therefore I am]''. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. Retrieved 14 October 2017.</ref> In May 2014, the British philosopher and [[literary critic]] [[Christopher Norris (critic)|Christopher Norris]] sent an email to Geoffrey Klempner with the following message: "I am sending (by attachment) a poem -- actually a long verse-essay -- that you might wish to publish in a forthcoming number of Philosophy Pathways. I should perhaps explain that the piece originates in my various published exchanges with Rorty many years back, and that it responds to his challenge that philosophy should become more adventurous, exploratory, inventive, metaphorical, and -- in short -- poetic. Hence my otherwise rather odd choice of verse as a medium in which to conduct philosophical debate." On the 1st of the following June, a couple of Norris' works were published in ''Philosophy Pathways''.<ref>''[https://philosophypathways.com/newsletter/issue186.html Special Christopher Norris Issue]''. ''Philosophy Pathways''. Issue No. 186. Retrieved 14 October 2017.</ref>
